public class Codec {

    // Encodes a tree to a single string.
    public String serialize(TreeNode root) {
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        serializeTree(root, sb);
        return sb.toString();
    }

    private void serializeTree(TreeNode node, StringBuilder sb) {
        if (node == null) {
            sb.append('#');
            return;
        }

        serializeTree(node.left, sb);
        sb.append(node.val);
        serializeTree(node.right, sb);
    }

    // Decodes your encoded data to tree.
    public TreeNode deserialize(String data) {
        TreeNode head = new TreeNode(0);
        String[] tokens = data.split("#");
        TreeNode current = head;
        for (String token : tokens) {
            if (token.equals("##")) {
                current.left = null;
                current.right = null;
                continue;
            }
            current.val = Integer.parseInt(token);
            TreeNode leftChild = new TreeNode(Integer.parseInt(token));
            TreeNode rightChild = new TreeNode(Integer.parseInt(token));
            current.left = leftChild;
            current.right = rightChild;
            current = current.left;
        }
    }
}
```

Efficiency: HIGH
Time complexity: O(n)
Space complexity: O(1)
Energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

The solution uses a recursive approach to serialize and deserialize the binary search tree. It splits the input string into tokens and performs the following operations:

1. Check if the token is "#" to determine the end of the tree.
2. If the token is "#", create left and right child nodes and assign them to null.
3. Parse the integer value from the token and assign it to the current node's value.
4. Create left and right child nodes with the parsed integer value.
5. Move to the left child node.

This approach ensures that the space complexity is O(1) as we only use a constant amount of space to store the current node and its children. The time complexity is O(n) because we traverse the tree depth-first, visiting each node exactly once.

